\subsection{Oppgave 4.6.11}

\subsubsection{a)} 
Det er fort gjort å sjekke at de to vektorene er lineært uavhengige. Resultatet følger av at enhver lineært uavhengig mengde med to elementer i $\R^2$ danner en 
basis for $\R^2$. 

\subsubsection{b)}
Vi radreduserer:
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(
\begin{array}{rrrr}
  1 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\
  1 &-1 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right)
&\sim&
\left(
\begin{array}{rrrr}
  1 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\
  0 &-2 &-1 & 1
\end{array}
\right) \\
&\sim&
\left(
\begin{array}{rrrr}
  1 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\
  0 & 1 & \frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right)
\sim
\left(
\begin{array}{rrrr}
  1 & 0 & \frac{1}{2} &  \frac{1}{2} \\
  0 & 1 & \frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right)
\end{eqnarray*}
Vi har derfor
\begin{eqnarray*}
  {\bf e}_1 &=& \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_1 + \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2 \\
  {\bf e}_2 &=& \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_1 - \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2.
\end{eqnarray*}

\subsubsection{c)} 
Dette følger fra Setning 4.6.12, og at ${\bf v}_1,{\bf v}_2$ er en basis for $\R^2$. 

\subsubsection{d)}
Kolonnene i $A$ er $T({\bf e}_1)$ og $T({\bf e}_2)$. Vi har 
\begin{eqnarray*}
  T({\bf e}_1) &=& T(\frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_1 + \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2) = \frac{1}{2} T({\bf v}_1) + \frac{1}{2} T({\bf v}_2) \\
               &=& \frac{1}{2} 2{\bf v}_1 - \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2 = {\bf v}_1 - \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2 \\
               &=& \left( \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 1\end{array} \right) - \frac{1}{2} \left( \begin{array}{r} 1 \\-1\end{array} \right) = \left( \begin{array}{r} \frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{3}{2} \end{array} \right) \\
  T({\bf e}_2) &=& T(\frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_1 - \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2) = \frac{1}{2} T({\bf v}_1) - \frac{1}{2} T({\bf v}_2) \\
               &=& \frac{1}{2} 2{\bf v}_1 + \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2 = {\bf v}_1 + \frac{1}{2} {\bf v}_2 \\
               &=& \left( \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 1\end{array} \right) + \frac{1}{2} \left( \begin{array}{r} 1 \\-1\end{array} \right) = \left( \begin{array}{r} \frac{3}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2} \end{array} \right).
\end{eqnarray*}
Vi får derfor 
\[
A
=
\left(
\begin{array}{rr}
  \frac{1}{2} & \frac{3}{2} \\
  \frac{3}{2} & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right).
\]